FOLLOWING DEPARTURE FROM TREASURE CAY BAHAMAS, THE CREW NOTED A HYDRAULIC SYSTEM WARNING LIGHT. THE CREW CONTINUED THE FLIGHT TO ITS DESTINATION, FORT LAUDERDALE, WITHOUT INCIDENT. ATC WAS ADVISED AND AN EMERGENCY DECLARED. AS A PRECAUTION, THE EMERGENCY GEAR EXTENSION PROCEDURE WAS COMPLETED. THE AIRCRAFT LANDED WITHOUT INCIDENT AND COMPLETED DEPLANING WITHOUT INTERRUPTION. INSPECTION REVEALED THE LEFT FLAP HYDRAULIC LOCKOUT LINE HAD BEEN VIBRATIONALLY POLISHED BY THE RUBBER INSULATION MATERIAL ATTACHED TO THE LOWER WING SKIN. THE POLISHING THINNED THE WALL THICKNESS OF THE TUBING TO THE POINT OF RUPTURE. DUE TO THE LOW CLEARANCE BETWEEN THE INSULATION AND THE LINE, VISUAL INSPECTION FOR CONTACT IS DIFFICULT. THE RUBBER SHEET HAD LOOSENED FROM THE HORIZONTAL SURFACE ABOVE THE HYDRAULIC LINES RUNNING LONGITUDINALLY IN THE UPPER WHEEL WELL. THE LINE WAS REPLACED, INCLUDING RE-ATTACHMENT OF THE INSULATION AND ADDITIONAL CHAFING PROTECTION WAS ADDED TO THE HYDRAULIC LINES IN THE LEFT AND RIGHT WHEEL WELLS. THE SYSTEM WAS CHECKED AND THE AIRCRAFT RETURNED TO SERVICE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

POWER ROLLBACK DURING FLIGHT, THE ENGINE ROLLED BACK TO 80 PERCENT NG IN AUTO MODE. THE PILOT SWITCHED TO MANUAL MODE AND THE ENGINE RECOVERED. AFTER LANDING AT BASE AND TROUBLESHOOTING, SUBSEQUENT START ATTEMPTS IN AUTO MODE RESULTED IN A HUNG START AT 40 PERCENT. NO STARTING ISSUES WERE NOTED WHEN IN MANUAL MODE. THE AUTOMATIC FUEL CONTROL WILL BE REPLACED.

ALTERNATOR COOLING FAN CAME APART IN FLIGHT AFTER TAKEOFF. PART OF COOLING FAN PUNCHED A HOLE IN INDUCTION AIR BOX DOWN STREAM OF AIR FILTER AND THE ALTERNATOR BELT CAME LOOSE IN THE ENGINE COMPARTMENT. LOSS OF ENGINE POWER FROM ENGINE FOD DAMAGE RESULTED IN AN UNEVENTFUL LANDING BACK TO THE AIRPORT. CREW WENT TO PERFORM A PREFLIGHT INSPECTION AND DISCOVERED THE BATTERY VOLTAGE WAS AT APPROXIMATELY 22.5 VOLTS AND THE BATTERY HOT LIGHT WAS ILLUMINATED. AFTER APPROXIMATELY 3.5 HRS THE BATTERY HAD COOLED TO A USEABLE TEMPERATURE. PRIOR TO THE NEXT FLIGHT, AS A PRECAUTION, THE BATTERY WAS REMOVED FOR INSPECTION AND A SERVICEABLE UNIT INSTALLED. THE REMOVED BATTERY WAS INSPECTED, DEEP CYCLED AND IS NOW APPROVED FOR RETURN TO SERVICE WITH NO DEFECTS NOTED. THE CAUSE OF THE OVERHEAT CONDITION IS BELIEVED TO BE THAT THE GPU PLUG WAS NOT FULLY INSERTED INTO THE AIRCRAFT ALLOWING FOR THE HIGH CURRENT DRAW OF THE AIR CONDITIONER TO BE DRAWN DIRECTLY FROM THE BATTERY. TO PREVENT A FUTURE OCCURRENCE, THE FLIGHT CREWS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO DISCONNECT THE SHIP’S BATTERY IF A GPU IS TO BE CONNECTED FOR ANYTHING OTHER THAN ENGINE START.

(CAN) DURING REPAIR, FUEL WAS NOTED DRIPPING FROM THE BELLY OF THE ACFT. INSPECTION REVEALED THE FUSELAGE FUEL TANK GRAVITY TRANSFER FLEX HOSE ASSEMBLIES WERE SATURATED WITH FUEL, DRIPPING AT A SLOW BUT STEADY RATE. THIS WOULD HAVE BEEN MISSED ON A NORMAL DAY, AS THE ACFT IS NORMALLY PARKED WITH NO FUEL IN THE FUSELAGE TANK. IF THE HOSE WERE TO RUPTURE IN FLIGHT, THERE WOULD BE NO STOPPING OF THE FUEL LEAK FROM THE FUSELAGE TANK AS IT IS A DIRECT LINK TO THE WINGS. THERE IS NO VALVE ISOLATING THE FUSELAGE TANK, ONLY A CHECK VALVE IN THE WINGS PREVENTING TRANSFER OF FUEL FROM WING TANKS TO THE FUSELAGE TANK. THE HOSES ARE LOCATED IN THE WHEEL WELL, THROUGH THE KEEL BEAM WITH THE BEACON/STROBE ASSY, WING HEAT DUCTS AND PRESSURIZATION DUCTS CLOSE BY. HOSES REPLACED WITH UPGRADED HOSES, PN 53A1101-101 AND 53A1101-102.

(CAN) ON CLIMB OUT HAD REAR BAY OVERHEAT COME ON INTERMITTENT THEN WENT OFF. THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS IN THE COCKPIT OTHER THAN THE NR2 ENGINE COMPUTER WENT TO MANUAL MODE. ON ARRIVAL, INSPECTION WAS CARRIED OUT AND FOUND THAT THE APU BLEED AIR DUCT FLEX COUPLING HT5-2-5-16 HAD BLOWN OFF. THE CLAMP SECURING THE FLEX COUPLING WAS IN PLACE BUT THE DUCT SLIPPED OUT OF THE FLEX COUPLING. THIS ALLOWED BLEED AIR FROM THE APU/ENGINE TO HEAT UP THE AREA WHERE THE NR2 ENGINE COMPUTER IS INSTALLED. THE NR2 ENGINE COMPUTER WARNING LIGHT WAS FLASHING IN THE COCKPIT AS REPORTED BY THE PILOT WHEN ARRIVED. THE ENGINE COMPUTER WAS DOWN LOADED AND REPORT SENT TO MFG FOR EVALUATION AS THE COMPUTER HAD FAULTS AND EXCEEDANCES. MFG ON THEIR RECOMMENDATION REQUIRED THE ENGINE TO BE REMOVED FOR AN OVER SPEED INSPECTION. THE FLEX DUCT, P/N HT5-2-5-16 HAS BEEN REPLACED WITH A WIGGINS FITTING P/N3605-32D COUPLING AND ORING MS9068-329 AS PER THE STC HOLDER PATS AIRCRAFT LLC.

WE RECEIVED PERMISSION FROM THE TOWER TO DO A GROUND RUN ON THE BUTTON OF THE RUNWAY TO ISOLATE THE PROBLEM. THE PROBLEM WAS ISOLATED TO THE RUDDER BOOST SYSTEM. MAINTENANCE ISOLATED THE DEFECT TO THE RIGHT ENGINE INSTRUMENT AND ENVIRONMENTAL BLEED VALVE BEING STUCK IN THE CLOSED POSITION. A NEW VALVE WAS INSTALLED AND THE SYSTEM GROUND FUNCTION CHECKED SERVICEABLE.

WHEN TESTING HYD SYS USING MOGEN AND SELECTING PRIMARY OFF, IT WOULD NOT. AFTER THE THIRD SELECTION TO OFF, IT FINALLY TURNED OFF SECURING PRESSURE TO PRIMARY WITH A CAUTION LIGHT ILLUMINATED. FURTHER CHECKS OF THE INTERLOCK SYSTEM WERE NORMAL. ON THE PREVIOUS FLIGHT 12 MAY, 2015 AUX HYDRAULICS WERE SECURED ON SHORT FINAL, SIMULATING AN INFLIGHT SYSTEM FAILURE, NOT ACTUAL, AND AT THIS TIME ON SHORT FINAL THE PRIMARY SYSTEM STARTED CYCLING ON AND OFF CAUSING BUFFETING AND VIBRATIONS IN THE CYCLIC CONTROL. AUX HYDRAULICS WERE IMMEDIATELY RESTORED AND AN UNEVENTFUL LANDING PERFORMED. UPON REACHING PARKING AND MAINTENANCE CHECKS PERFORMED ALL SYSTEMS OPERATED NORMAL. ON 13 MAY, 2015 AFTER FURTHER TROUBLESHOOTING MAINTENANCE TECHS ISOLATED THE FAULT TO BE THE PRIMARY HYDRAULICS PRESSURE SWITCH. REPLACEMENT WITH AN O/H UNIT RETURNED THE SYSTEMS TO NORMAL OPERATION.

ABOUT 5 MIN AFTER TAKEOFF, WE SMELLED A MELTING PLASTIC SMELL. IT WAS MOST PREVALENT FROM THE GALLEY FWD, IT PERSISTED THE REST OF THE FLIGHT. COMPLIED WITH ETN EM- 72-034, ENG ODOR EVENT. NO ODORS. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, FOUND HOT JUG PLUG SCORCHED & BURNED.
FS 280 FRAME CORRODED BETWEEN STRINGERS 23RT-23LT. REMOVED CORROISON FROM FRAME IAW SRM 57-21-06-001-001-A01. MAJOR REPAIR.

PILOT REPORTED, CABIN WENT TO MAXIMUM DIFERENTIAL PRESSURE DURING CLIMBOUT AND REMAINED AT MAXIMUM DIFERENTIAL THROUGHOUT THE FLIGHT. CABIN HAD TO BE MANUALLY DUMPED FOR DESCENT/LANDING. FOUND PLASTIC TUBING IN PEDESTAL, FROM CONTROLLER TO OUTFLOW VALVE, HAD MELTED THRU, RENDERING CONTROLLER INEFFICTIVE. THE TUBING HAD BEEN IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO A BUSS FEED WIRE WHICH HAD OVERHEATED AND MELTED THE TUBING. THE CAUSE OF THE OVERHEATING WAS TRACED TO A BUTT SPLICE IN THE WIRE A FEW INCHES FROM ITS TERMINATING POINT AT A DIODE MOUNTED ON A HEAT SINK. IT IS SUSPECTED THE SPLICE WAS NOT FULLY CRIMPED RESULTING IN A HIGH RESISTANCE WHICH OVERHEATED THE SHORT WIRE RUN TO THE DIODE. THE ENTIRE WIRE, FROM THE CIRCUIT BREAKER TO THE DIODE WAS REPLACED. THE CIRCUT BREAKER WAS REPLACED, AS PRECAUTION, AS WELL AS THE DIODE, SHOWED SIGNS OF HEAT DISTRESS. THE TUBING WAS REPAIRED AND ROUTED AWAY FROM THE WIRING. SYSTEMS CHECKS WERE GOOD. IT IS SUGGESTED THAT SPLICES, IF NECESSARY TO INSTALL, BE CRIMPED WITH THE PROPER TOOLS AND CHECKED FOR PROPER INSTALLATION.

MAINTENANCE DISCOVERED THAT THE KEVLAR CABLE CAM BASE BRACKET FOR THE TAILCONE WAS WORN, OUT OF ALLOWABLE LIMITS. THE KEVLAR CABLE CAM BASE BRACKET WAS REPLACED AND THE SYSTEM WAS RIGGED TO SPECIFICATIONS. THE FUNCTIONAL CHECK WAS COMPLETED SATISFACTORILY.

WHEN THE ACFT LANDED WITH THE INTENTION OF PERFORMING A TOUCH AND GO, THE PILOTS BECAME AWARE OF A VIBRATION THAT INCREASED TO A SEVERE RATTLING OF THE AIRFRAME. THE IP DECIDED TO BRAKE, ABORTING THE TAKEOFF, AND REALIZED THE ACFT WAS SUFFERING FROM A DEFLATED LEFT TIRE. THE ACFT BECAME DISABLED ON THE RUNWAY AND HAD TO BE TOWED TO THE APRON. REPLACED THE WHEEL ASSEMBLY. UPON INSPECTION OF THE WHEEL ASSEMBLY, THE TUBE WAS FOUND TO HAVE A SMALL HOLE 6" FROM THE VALVE STEM ON THE SIDE OF THE TIRE. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF FOLDING, CREASING, OR OTHER WEAR OF THE TUBE, BOTH INSIDE AND OUT. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE WHEEL ASSEMBLIES SERVICED BY THIS REPAIR STATION ARE SERVICED WITH NITROGEN ONLY.

AIRCRAFT WAS GROUNDED: FLT ATTENDANT REPORTED "WAXY SMELL" ON DECENT FROM ABOUT 10,000 UNTIL CABIN DOOR WAS OPENED AT GATE. MAINTENANCE CONFIRMED THE SOURCE WAS FROM THE APU. MAINTENANCE RAN ENGINES FOR APPROX. 1 HOUR WITH NO SMELL IN A/C (APU SELECTED OFF). ***SUPPLEMENTAL INFORMATION: MAINTENANCE REMOVED AND REPLACED APU IAW CARD 26L31049005 AND ACCOMPLISHED CARD 26L00021002 AND 26L00021004.***(CLOSED)

AT 30 MIN CRUISE FLIGHT @ FL400, CAPTAIN (PF) NOTICED LT SIDE PFD IAS FLAG, AND VERBALIZED TO PNF. PF COMPARED PFDS AND STBY ASI. RT SIDE PFD AND STBY ASIS INDICATED APPRX 20KTS FASTER (220KTS) THAN LT SIDE. OVER THE COURSE OF 30SEC, AIRSPEED CONTINUED TO DECAY BELOW 200KTS ON LT SIDE PFD AND DECREASED AT SAME RATE ON BOTH RT SIDE PFD AND STBY. PF DEEMED A DESCENT NECESSARY TO TRADE ALTITUDE FOR AIRSPEED. PNF ASKED ATC FOR LOWER ALTITUDE. PF INITIATED A ~3000FPM DESCENT AND AIRSPEED CONTINUED TO DECAY TOWARD 140KTS ON ALL ASIS. PF QUICKLY REALIZED ALL AIRSPEED INFORMATION WAS ERRONEOUS AND SUSPECTED STUCK PITOT. BOTH PILOTS VERIFIED PITOT HEATS-ON AND CIRCUIT BREAKERS-IN. PF DECREASED DESCENT TO 1000FPM, SET A KNOWN POWER SETTING AND REFERENCED AOA .2. IAS PEGGED AT 40KTS ON BOTH PFDS AND 0KTS ON STBY. PNF DECLARED EMERGENCY AND ASKED FOR VECTORS TO KSLN. PNF RAN LOSS OF AIRSPEED INDICATION CHECKLIST AND REVIEWED LOSS OF AIRSPEED APPROACH CHECKLIST. ALL ASIS RETURNED TO NORMAL @ ~FL260 AND INDICATED SIMILAR AIRSPEEDS. PF FLEW ILS UNEVENTFULLY INTO KSLN.

DURING STRAIGHT AND LEVEL FLIGHT THE CREW RECEIVED AN ADVISORY MESSAGE THAT HYDRAULIC QUANTITY WAS LOW. SHORTLY AFTER THAT THE CREW NOTICED THAT THE HYDRAULIC SYSTEM PRESSURE STARTED DECLINING AND RECEIVED A LOW HYDRAULIC PRESSURE ANNUNCIATION. THE CREW DIVERTED TO THE CLOSEST AIRPORT AND USED THE LANDING GEAR FREEFALL EXTENSION METHOD AND EMERGENCY BRAKING WHEN ON THE GROUND. DURING VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE MAIN HYDRAULIC SYSTEM BY MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT A UNION THAT UTILIZES A PACKING. WHEN UNION WAS DISASSEMBLED THE PACKING WAS FOUND TO BE TORN. A NEW PACKING WAS INSTALLED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE MANUFACTURES PARTS MANUAL. THE UNION WAS REASSEMBLED. THE MAIN HYDRAULIC SYSTEM FILTERS WERE INSPECTED FOR CONTAMINATION WITH NONE FOUND. THE HYDRAULIC SYSTEM WAS THEN SERVICED AND FUNCTION TESTED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE MANUFACTURES MAINTENANCE MANUAL. NO FURTHER DEFECTS WERE NOTED AND THE AIRCRAFT WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE.

REPETITIVE FAILURES OF NOSE WHEEL STEERING FAILURE. AFTER EXTENSIVE HOURS OF TROUBLESHOOTING CONTACT WITH LEARJET ENGINEERING SUPPORT, AND REPLACEMENT OF THE NOSE WHEEL STEERING SERVO, WE HAVE FOUND THAT THE PROBLEM WAS DUE TO A BAD NR 4 MAIN WHEEL SPEED SENSOR (TRANSDUCER). NOTHING IN THE MAINTENANCE MANUAL OR TROUBLESHOOTING PROCEDURES EVEN SUGGESTS THAT A WHEEL SPEED SENSOR CAN CAUSE THIS PROBLEM. THE TECHNICIANS HERE DID A GOOD JOB OF ISOLATING AND FINDING THE PROBLEM. IN REALITY, LEARJET DID NOT HAVE AN EXPLANATION FOR WHAT WAS HAPPENING. THE LEAD TECHNICIAN REALIZED THAT THE FAILURE WAS NOT OCCURRING WHILE PERFORMING THE OPERATION CHECKS STATICALLY. IT ONLY OCCURRED WHILE TAXING AND AT A CERTAIN SPEED. IN SHORT, THE NR 4 SPEED SENSOR WAS FAILING ONLY AT ABOUT THE 10 KNOT RANGE OF WHEEL SPEED. AT ZERO KNOTS AND ABOVE 50 KNOTS THE SENSOR WAS OK, BUT AT AROUND 10 KNOTS THE COMPUTER SHOWED EXTREME ERRATIC READINGS. THE COMPUTER SHOWED ALL OTHER WHEEL SPEED SENSORS OPERATING NORMALLY.

APPROXIMATELY 20 HOURS AFTER ANNUAL, THE VERNIER MIXTURE CONTROL BECAME VERY STIFF. THERE WERE NO KNOWN ANOMALIES OR WEAR NOTED AT THE ANNUAL. DUE TO THE AGE OF THE PART, IT WAS REPLACED. UPON, DISASSEMBLY THE VERNIER PART OF THE CONTROL APPEARED TO STILL WORK APPROPRIATELY, BUT THERE APPEARED TO BE A LARGE AMOUNT OF BLACK MATERIAL THAT HAD BUILT UP ON THE LENGTH OF THE CABLE (ESPECIALLY NEAR THE TOP OF THE CABLE ASSEMBLE, NEAR THE TOP OF THE VERNIER CONTROL). THE CABLE APPEARED TO BE GUMMY IN NATURE. UPON POLLING OWNERS, SOME OWNERS MAY HAVE USED SANITIZER THAT INCLUDED PHENOLS AND/OR METHANOL THAT MAY HAVE BROKEN DOWN THE BLACK PHENOLIC HOUSING OF THE VERNIER MIXTURE. A LIGHT LOCALIZED CLEANING REMOVED THE RESIDUE AND APPEARED TO BE INCONSISTENT WITH DIRT.

ON 1-14-2021, DURING A FSDO 141 INSPECTION OF CESSNA 172N, REGISTRATION N738HX, THE COPILOT’S SEAT WAS FOUND TO HAVE .040 SAFETY WIRE SECURING THE SEAT BACK RECLINING LOCKING MECHANISM TO THE SEAT BACK PIVOT POINT. THIS RESULTED IN THE SEAT BACK BEING LOCKED IN A FIXED UP-RIGHT POSITION. THE SAFETY WIRE WAS INSTALLED BY PARTIES UNKNOWN. THE RECLINING ADJUSTMENT HANDLE WAS SHEARED AND FLOATING FREELY. AD 2011-10-09, WHICH SUPERCEDES AD 87-20-03 R2, ADDRESSES ONLY THE INSPECTION OF THE SEAT RAILS/TRACK. IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT AD 2011-10-09, WHICH ONLY ADDRESSES FAILURE OF THE SEAT FORE-AND-AFT LOCKING MECHANISM, BE AMENDED TO INCLUDE INSPECTION OF THE SEAT RECLINING MECHANISM AND THE HEIGHT ADJUSTING MECHANISM, IF INCORPORATED. UNANTICIPATED FAILURE OF EITHER OF THESE SYSTEMS CAN RESULT IN THE SEAT OCCUPANT INADVERTENTLY GRASPING THE CONTROL YOKE, RESULTING IN AN ABRUPT CONTROL INPUT INDUCING A POTENTIAL LOSS OF CONTROL.

DURING TEST FLIGHT FOR THE INSTALLATION OF AUTOPILOT SYSTEM GENESYS S-TEC3100 INTO THE DHC-6 AIRCRAFT SEVERAL PROBLEMS BECAME APPARENT. THESE ISSUES WERE: PITCH UP DURING INITIALISATION; CONCERN PITCH UP ON FIRST SELECTION OF AP; AP UNABLE TO MAINTAIN LEVEL FLIGHT WITH FLAP DEFLECTION/RETRACTION; AP APPROACH MODE IS UNABLE TO FLY MANUFACTURER RECOMMENDED APPROACH SPEED; AP APPROACH MODE IS INACCURATE; AP APPROACH MODE FAIL DURING RNP APPROACH; AP LABELS ARE INCORRECT FOR RNP APPROACH; EN ROUTE GPS STEERING INACCURATE; AP CONTROL COLUMN CONTROLS CONTRADICTORY TO STANDARD AIRCRAFT. THESE ISSUES WERE RESOLVED BY SOFTWARE UPDATE 1.4.1 HOWEVER THERE STILL REMAINS A CONCERN OVER BALLOONING ON APPROACH WITH FIRST STAGE FLAP (F10) IS SELECTED, THE AIRCRAFT INCREASES ALTITUDE BY 300FT. GENESYS S-TEC HAVE BEEN INFORMED AND MITIGATIONS ARE IN PLACE TO REDUCE THE RISK OF AN ACCIDENT. THIS HAS BEEN REPORTED TO UK CAA AIR SAFETY SUPPORT INTERNATIONAL (ASSI) DUE TO THE AIRCRAFT BEING REGISTERED IN THE FALKLAND ISLANDS, HOWEVER BRITISH ANTARCTIC SURVEY HAVE AN ICAO REQUIREMENT TO REPORT TO THE FAA AS THE STATE OF DESIGN OF THE AP SYSTEM FAILURE. AN SDR WAS ALSO SUBMITTED TO TRANSPORT CANADA BY ROCKY MOUNTAIN AIRCRAFT, REF. 20210823010.

DURING 100 HOUR INSPECTION, NOTICED AN EXCESSIVE AMOUNT OF EXHAUST RESIDUE BUILDUP IN COWLING, ON ENGINE, AND ON FIREWALL. FURTHER INSPECTION FOUND THAT BOTH THE NUMBER 2 AND NUMBER 4 EXHAUST PIPES WERE EXCESSIVELY LOOSE AND HAD A LOT OF PLAY. THE AMOUNT OF MOVEMENT IS EXCESSIVE AND IS ALLOWING EXHAUST BY-PRODUCTS TO ESCAPE THE EXHAUST SYSTEM IN THE ENGINE BAY, RATHER THAN BEING CONTAINED WITHIN THE EXHAUST SYSTEM AND BEING BLOWN OUT OF THE TAIL PIPE. THE TWO PIPES HAD ALSO BEEN RUBBING AGAINST EACH OTHER WHICH LED TO CHAFING OF BOTH PIPES. INSPECTED 4 OTHER AIRCRAFT WE OPERATE AND FOUND THAT ALL 4 AIRCRAFT HAD LOOSE EXHAUST PIPES WITH EXCESSIVE PLAY/MOVEMENT AND EXCESSIVE EXHAUST RESIDUE IN AND AROUND THE COWLING. CONCERNS OF NOT ONLY CARBON MONOXIDE, BUT ALSO HOW THE EXHAUST LEAK WILL AFFECT OTHER COMPONENTS IN THE ENGINE BAY. ISSUE HAS BEEN RASIED WITH CIRRUS.

UNABLE TO PROPERLY CLOSE MAIN CABIN DOOR. LEVER COMES DOWN AND ALL GREEN STRIPES LINE UP, BUT UNABLE TO PULL PLUNGER. IT PULLS ABOUT HALFWAY AND SPRINGS BACK REMAINING "RED" (NO GREEN) AND DAYLIGHT OBSERVED THROUGH CIRCLE WINDOW. ALSO HAD PAX DOOR OUT HNDL AMBER CAS ILLUMINATE AT THIS TIME. OPENED AND CLOSED DOOR MULTIPLE TIMES WITH SAME RESULT. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE AIRCRAFT, MET WITH THE CREW BEFORE THEIR DEPARTURE. THEY PROVIDED A DETAILED ACCOUNT OF THE DOOR FAULT THEY EXPERIENCED. TO INVESTIGATE, I OPERATED THE DOOR MULTIPLE TIMES ALONGSIDE THE CREW BUT WAS UNABLE TO REPLICATE THE ISSUE DURING OUR TESTS. AFTER NOTIFYING THE MAINTENANCE CONTROL CENTER (MCC) ABOUT OUR FINDINGS AND CONSIDERING THE DOOR'S REPAIR HISTORY, IT WAS DECIDED TO KEEP THE AIRCRAFT GROUNDED. WE MOVED THE AIRCRAFT TO THE HANGAR FOR A DETAILED INSPECTION OF THE DOOR AND TO PERFORM THE NECESSARY TROUBLESHOOTING. TECHNICIANS MANAGED TO REPLICATE THE FAULT. THEY REMOVED THE TWO FORWARD ACCESS PANELS FROM THE MED (LABELED AND BAGGED NEXT TO THE AIRCRAFT ON A CART) AND CONDUCTED AN INSPECTION OF THE INNER MECHANISMS. DURING THIS INSPECTION, THEY DISCOVERED THAT ITEM 47 ROD WAS NOT SECURE AND HAD A WEAKENED SPRING. AFTER REMOVING THIS ROD, THE OUTER DOOR HANDLE BECAME SIGNIFICANTLY EASIER TO OPERATE, AND THE DOOR FUNCTIONED PROPERLY AFTER SEVERAL OPENINGS AND CLOSINGS. RELEVANT REFERENCES INCLUDE CL650 AMM AMM 52-11-00, 52-11-07, 52-11-10, AND CL650 IPC 52-11-15. BASED ON THIS FINDING, THE TECHNICIANS RESEARCHED THE TECHNICAL DATA AND PROVIDED THE MCC/SITE REPRESENTATIVE WITH THE PART NUMBERS NEEDED FOR REPLACEMENT. ITEM 70 IS THE ROD THAT WAS FOUND UNSECURED DURING THE INSPECTION, AND THE SITE REPRESENTATIVE WAS INFORMED ABOUT THIS. THE ROD, LOCK WASHERS, AND COTTER PINS WILL NEED TO BE REPLACED ONCE THEY ARE DELIVERED, ACCORDING TO REFERENCES CL650 AMM AMM 52-11-00, 52-11-07, 52-11-10, AND CL650 IPC 52-11-15. MULTIPLE TECHNICIANS REMOVED THE OLD ROD ASSEMBLY, SPRING, AND FLAP DOOR (PN 601R38649-3 NSN) DUE TO THE CABIN DOOR HANDLE SHOWING AN AMBER CAUTION ALERT, WHICH PREVENTED THE PROPER CLOSURE OF THE MAIN CABIN DOOR. THEY THEN INSTALLED A NEW ROD ASSEMBLY, SPRING, AND FLAP DOOR (PN 601R38649-3 NSN), SUPPLIED BY THE CUSTOMER, ALSO REFERENCING CL650 AMM AMM 52-11-00, 52-11-07, 52-11-10, AND CL650 IPC 52-11-15. DURING THE OPERATIONAL CHECK, TECHNICIANS HAD TO MAKE ADJUSTMENTS DUE TO LIMITED ACCESS, WHICH TOOK ADDITIONAL TIME. THE OPERATIONAL CHECK WAS SUCCESSFUL, AND THE TECHNICIANS CLOSED THE ACCESS PANELS BACK TO FLIGHT CONFIGURATION. TECHNICIANS ALSO INSTALLED 2 NEW CUSTOMER-SUPPLIED COTTER PINS MS24665-153 AND WERE CLEARED TO INSTALL THE NEW PRESSURE VALVE DOOR SPRING ROD PROVIDED BY THE CUSTOMER. THE INSTALLATION OF THE SPRING ROD WAS INSPECTED BY RII - DENNIS ROSS, IN ACCORDANCE WITH CL-650 AMM 52-11-04. ROSS ALSO VERIFIED THE ADJUSTMENT OF THE PRESSURE VALVE DOOR AND SPRING ROD PER CL-650 AMM 52-11-00. FINALLY, DENNIS ROSS CONDUCTED AN OPERATIONAL CHECK AND CONFIRMED THAT THERE WERE NO ERROR MESSAGES RELATED TO THE MAIN ENTRY DOOR, ACCORDING TO CL-650 AMM 52-11-00. THE OPERATIONAL CHECK WAS SUCCESSFUL, AND THE INNER T-HANDLE OPERATED NORMALLY, WITH ALL MESSAGES INDICATING CORRECT HANDLE POSITION. ORIGINAL SUBMISSION DATE: 4-25-2025

APPROXIMATELY 1 HR INTO FLT AT FL410, AUTOPILOT DISCONNECTED WITHOUT ANY AURAL IND. ATTEMPTED TO RE-ENGAGE AUTOPILOT BUT DID NOT ENGAGE. NO ANNUNCIATED FD MODES & SEVERAL UNSUCCESSFUL ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO SELECT ROLL & PITCH MODES WITH FD CONTROL PANEL. FD COMMAND BARS ON PILOT’S EADI REMAINED OUT OF VIEW. PILOT’S EHSI SHOWED A RED X ACROSS INSTRUMENT & APPEARED HEADING INFO NOT VALID. PILOT RESUMED MANUAL HAND-FLYING ACFT RELYING ON STDBY INST. CO-PILOT’S FD REMAINED IN VIEW BUT HAD NO WAY OF SETTING HEADING USING HEADING BUG, IT WAS NOT OPERABLE VIA REMOTE CONTROLLER. NO VISIBLE HEADING BUG ON PILOT’S PFD OR MFD. NO PRESELECT ALTITUDE VALUE VISIBLE ON PILOT’S PFD OR MFD, ONLY DASHES. PILOT ATTEMPTED TO REVERT TO CO-PILOT’S HEADING SYS, USING HEADING REVERSION BUTTON, NO SUCCESS. MFD DISPLAYED “MENU INOP. DECISION MADE TO DECLARE AN EMERGENCY & DIVERT TO KCLT WHERE VFR WX REPORTED & A VISUAL APPROACH CONDUCTED. A NORMAL LANDING MADE IN KCLT. MX FOUND EFIS CONTL 1 C/B TRIPPED. RESET BREAKER & OPS CHKD A/P & OTHER SYS & COULD NOT DUPLICATE FAILURE. WHEN DESCRIBING THE EVENTS TO MAINTENANCE, ONE OF THE ITEMS THE PILOT MENTIONED WAS AN ISSUE WITH THE PILOTS PUSH TO TALK SWITCH NOT WORKING. AT THE TIME IT WAS BELIEVED TO BE UNRELATED TO THE AVIONICS ISSUE BUT WE DID HAVE MAINTENANCE CHECK IT. THEY COULD NOT DUPLICATE ANY ISSUE WITH IT AND FOUND IT TO OPERATE NORMALLY. THE NEXT DAY WHEN THE CREW WAS PREPARING TO DEPART THEY REPORTED IT WASN’T WORKING AGAIN SO IT WAS DEFERRED PER THE MEL. IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT THE REASON THE SWITCH WAS INTERMITTENT WAS BECAUSE IT WAS GETTING PRESSED TOO DEEP INTO THE YOKE SWITCH BUSHING. IF THE SWITCH WAS PRESSED TOO HARD IT WOULD COME INTO CONTACT WITH THE AUTO-PILOT DISCONNECT SWITCH CONTACT IN THE YOKE AND TRIP THE CB.

DEPARTING KSRQ 9/18/25, THE CREW NOTICED THE CABIN FIRE WARNING LIGHT ILLUMINATED. THE SYSTEM SENSOR IS IN THE CABIN AREA BAGGAGE COMPARTMENT. THE CAPTAIN INSTRUCTED THE FO TO GO BACK AND VISUALLY INSPECT THE BAGGAGE COMPARTMENT. NO SMOKE WAS NOTICED. THE CAPTAIN REPORTED THAT THE LIGHT WOULD COME ON AND GO OUT WITH POWER LEVER ADJUSTMENTS SO HE ELECTED TO DIVERT INTO KOPF. THE LIGHT WENT OUT AND STAYED OUT DESCENDING INTO OPF. AND THERE WAS STILL NO SMOKE SMELL. THE AIRCRAFT WAS LANDED SAFELY IN OPF. LOCAL MAINTENANCE INSPECTED THE BAGGAGE SMOKE DETECTOR SYSTEM AND FOUND THAT WHEN THE SENSOR WAS MOVED, THE LIGHT WOULD FLICKER. A NEW SMOKE DETECTOR/SENSOR WAS ORDERED AND INSTALLED. THE ISSUE COULD NOT BE DUPLICATED AS BEFORE AND THE SMOKE DETECTION SYSTEM TESTED NORMALLY. THE AIRCRAFT HAS COMPLETED TWO FLIGHTS SINCE THE DIVERSION WITH NO ISSUES REPORTED.
